, several degrees of onychodystrophy and nail shedding. Dental abnormalities, when survival enables their observation, include regularly marked hypoplasia or complete absence of enamel. Frequent ocular lesions comprise corneal blisters, erosions and scarring, and ectropion formation. Failure to thrive is an almost constant finding, and multifactorial anemia is also common.", "etiology": "Severe JEB is caused by mutations in one of the three laminin-332 coding genes: LAMA3 (18q11.2), LAMB3 (1q32) and LAMC2 (1q25-q31). In most cases, null mutations are found on both alleles of the causative gene.", "diagnostic_methods": "In addition to the finding of a cleavage plane located within the lamina lucida of the cutaneous basement membrane zone, a negative immunofluorescence staining for laminin-332 is typical of severe JEB. However, in rare cases the staining is strongly reduced and thus does not enable differentiation of severe JEB from intermediate JEB. In these cases, genetic testing, showing null mutations in one of the three genes encoding laminin-332, is necessary to confirm the diagnosis.", "differential_diagnosis": "Differential diagnosis includes other types epidermolysis bullosa, in particular congenital autoimmune bullous diseases.", "antenatal_diagnosis": "Prenatal diagnosis should always be recommended and diseases-causing pathogenic variants should be disclosed in advance.", "genetic_counseling": "Transmission is autosomal recessive. Genetic counseling should be offered to at-risk couples (both individuals are carriers of a disease-causing mutation) informing them of the 25% risk of having an affected child at each pregnancy.", "management_and_treatment": "The approach is multidisciplinary with neonatal pathology units for severely affected patients, antibiotics for pulmonary infections, local antisepsis for slow-healing lesions and advanced dressing for the treatment of ulcers. Nutritional support is mandatory.", "prognosis": "Prognosis is poor and the most severe JEB patients die in the first few years of life, with the major causes of death being failure to thrive, respiratory failure, sepsis, and pneumonia. Some rare patients with generalized cutaneous and internal disease reach the age of 10-15 years. In addition, squamous cell carcinomas may arise in a minority of severe JEB patients (4.5% according to data from the U.S. National EB Registry)."}, {"name": "Epidermolysis bullosa letalis", "sub_name": "Epidermolysis bullosa, junctionale, generalisierte schwere", "german_description": "In den Vereinigten Staaten und Italien wurde \u00fcber eine Pr\u00e4valenz bei Neugeborenen von 1/2.500.000 und 1/1.470.000 Lebendgeburten berichtet, bei Neugeborenen in den Niederlanden von 1/250.000 Lebendgeburten. Nach den US-amerikanischen und italienischen Registern haben etwa 20 % der Patienten mit JEB den schwereren Typ Herlitz.", "english": 1, "defenition": "A severe form of junctional epidermolysis bullosa (JEB) characterized by blisters and extensive erosions, localized to the skin and mucous membranes.", "synonyms": "Epidermolysis bullosa letalis, JEB-H, Junctional epidermolysis bullosa generalisata gravis, Junctional epidermolysis bullosa, Herlitz type, Junctional epidermolysis bullosa, Herlitz-Pearson type, Severe generalized JEB, ", "prevalence": "1-9 / 1 000 000", "inheritance": "Autosomal recessive\u00a0", "age_of_onset": "Infancy, Neonatal", "icd_10": "Q81.1", "omim": "226700", "umls": "C0079683", "gard": "2153", "epidemiology": "Prevalence at birth is estimated to range between 1/200,000-2,500,000 worldwide. According to data from U.S. and Italian EB registries, about 20% of patients with JEB have the severe type.", "clinical_description": "The extreme severity of this condition is apparent at birth. Bullae present spontaneously even with a gentle touch, with an onset within the first several months to one to two years of life. After the eruption, blisters lose their roof and remain visible as erosions that do not hea